Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
Full blockage, robbing out and dumping.

Locus 25 is the blockage of the doorway leading into the ‘anteroom’ from the ‘colonnaded corridor.’ It is poorly made, with apparently no attempt made to make the north face finished – the ashlars of which it is comprised intrude quite far into the room and on top of the floor. There are five courses to the blockage, composed of hewn and dressed sandstone ashlars with snecking stones. This locus was removed at the end of the season primarily for creating easy access into the ‘bathroom’ for tourists. As a result, we have a clearer picture of the few inclusions jammed into the dry-laid wall, which included small amounts of pottery, bone, and glass. It appears that this blockage occurred just before the dumping in the ‘anteroom’ and ‘bathroom,’ as it finally closed off this space to allow for such use. As such, it is phased to Stage 5, when that final blockage and dumping occurred.
Full blockage of the narrowed door of the ‘anteroom’
